# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: engine-displacement
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] GM's Active Fuel Management technology used a solenoid to deactivate the lifters on selected cylinders of a pushrod V-layout engine.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] GM used the Active Fuel Management technology on a range of engines including with the GM Small Block Gen IV engine family, first-generation GM EcoTec3 engine family, second-generation GM High-Feature V6 DOHC engine family, and first-generation High-Feature V8 DOHC engine family.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] Vehicle applications included the 2005 Chevy TrailBlazer EXT, the GMC Envoy XL, Envoy XUV, and Pontiac Grand Prix.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] General Motors was the first to modify existing production engines to enable cylinder deactivation, with the introduction of the Cadillac *L62* "V8-6-4" in 1981.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] In 2004, the electronics side was improved greatly with the introductions of Electronic Throttle Control, electronically controlled transmissions, and transient engine and transmission controls.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] In addition, computing power was vastly increased.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] A solenoid control valve assembly integrated into the engine valley cover contains solenoid valves that provide a pressurized oil signal to specially designed hydraulic roller lifters provided by Eaton Corp. and Delphi.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] These lifters disable and re-enable exhaust and intake valve operation to deactivate and reactivate engine cylinders .
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] Unlike the first generation system, only half of the cylinders can be deactivated.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] It is notable that the second generation system uses engine oil to hydraulically modulate engine valve function.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] As a result, the system is dependent upon the quality of the oil in the engine.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] As anti-foaming agents in engine oil are depleted, air may become entrained or dissolve in the oil, delaying the timing of hydraulic control signals.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] Similarly engine oil viscosity and cleanliness is a factor.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] SAE 10W40 instead of SAE 5W30, or the failure to change the engine oil or oil filter at factory recommended intervals, can also significantly impair system performance.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] In 2001, GM showcased the 2002 Cadillac Cien concept car, which featured Northstar XV12 engine with Displacement on Demand.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] Later that year, GM debuted Opel Signum² concept car in Frankfurt Auto Show, which uses the global XV8 engine with displacement on demand.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] In 2003, GM unveiled the Cadillac Sixteen concept car at the Detroit Opera House, which featured an XV16 concept engine that can switch between 4, 8, and 16 cylinders.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] On April 8, 2003, General Motors announced this technology (now called Active Fuel Management) to be commercially available on 2005 GMC Envoy XL, Envoy XUV and Chevrolet TrailBlazer EXT using optional Vortec 5300 V8 engine.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] GM also extended the technology on the new High Value *LZ8* V6 engine in the Chevrolet Impala and Monte Carlo as well as the 5.3L V8 LS4 engine in the last generation Chevrolet Impala SS, Monte Carlo SS and Pontiac Grand Prix GXP.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] In both designs, half of the cylinders can be switched off under light loads.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] On July 21, 2008, General Motors unveiled the production version of the 2010 Chevrolet Camaro.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] The Camaro SS with an automatic transmission features the GM L99 engine, a development of the LS3 with Active Fuel Management which allowed it to run on four cylinders during light load conditions.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] In January 2018, GM announced an improved version of AFM called *Dynamic Fuel Management* to be initially released in Chevy Silverado trucks.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] This system shuts off any number of cylinders in a variety of combinations, maximizing fuel economy and avoiding switching between banks of cylinders.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] This is achieved by using oil pressure solenoids to collapse each individual hydraulic valve lifter, allowing for fully independent individual cylinder control.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] The system is based on *Dynamic Skip Fire,* a technology developed by California company Tula Technology.
[src:engine-displacement/active-fuel-management] The 6.2L V8 engine of the Chevrolet Silverado incorporating the technology was named one of Ward's 10 Best Engines for 2019.
[src:engine-displacement/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:engine-displacement/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:engine-displacement/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:engine-displacement/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:engine-displacement/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:engine-displacement/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:engine-displacement/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:engine-displacement/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:engine-displacement/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:engine-displacement/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:engine-displacement/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:engine-displacement/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:engine-displacement/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:engine-displacement/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:engine-displacement/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:engine-displacement/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:engine-displacement/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:engine-displacement/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:engine-displacement/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:engine-displacement/alternator-automotive] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] In geometry, the area enclosed by a circle of radius r is π*r*2.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Here, the Greek letter π represents the constant ratio of the circumference of any circle to its diameter, approximately equal to 3.14159.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] One method of deriving this formula, which originated with Archimedes, involves viewing the circle as the limit of a sequence of regular polygons with an increasing number of sides.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The area of a regular polygon is half its perimeter multiplied by the distance from its center to its sides, and because the sequence tends to a circle, the corresponding formula—that the area is half the circumference times the radius—namely, *A* = ⁠1/2⁠ × 2π*r* × *r*, holds for a circle.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Although often referred to as the area of a circle in informal contexts, strictly speaking, the term *disk* refers to the interior region of the circle, while circle is reserved for the boundary only, which is a curve and covers no area itself.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Therefore, the *area of a disk* is the more precise phrase for the area enclosed by a circle.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Modern mathematics can obtain the area using the methods of integral calculus or its more sophisticated offspring, real analysis.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] However, the area of a disk was studied by the Ancient Greeks.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Eudoxus of Cnidus in the fifth century B.C. had found that the area of a disk is proportional to its radius squared.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Archimedes used the tools of Euclidean geometry to show that the area inside a circle is equal to that of a right triangle whose base has the length of the circle's circumference and whose height equals the circle's radius in his book *Measurement of a Circle*.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The circumference is 2*πr*, and the area of a triangle is half the base times the height, yielding the area *πr*2 for the disk.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Prior to Archimedes, Hippocrates of Chios was the first to show that the area of a disk is proportional to the square of its diameter, as part of his quadrature of the lune of Hippocrates, but did not identify the constant of proportionality.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] A variety of arguments have been advanced historically to establish the equation $A=\pi r^{2}$ to varying degrees of mathematical rigor.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The most famous of these is Archimedes' method of exhaustion, one of the earliest uses of the mathematical concept of a limit, as well as the origin of Archimedes' axiom which remains part of the standard analytical treatment of the real number system.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The original proof of Archimedes is not rigorous by modern standards, because it assumes that we can compare the length of arc of a circle to the length of a secant and a tangent line, and similar statements about the area, as geometrically evident.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The area of a regular polygon is half its perimeter times the apothem.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] As the number of sides of the regular polygon increases, the polygon tends to a circle, and the apothem tends to the radius.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] This suggests that the area of a disk is half the circumference of its bounding circle times the radius.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Following Archimedes' argument in *The Measurement of a Circle* (c.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] 260 BCE), compare the area enclosed by a circle to a right triangle whose base has the length of the circle's circumference and whose height equals the circle's radius.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] If the area of the circle is not equal to that of the triangle, then it must be either greater or less.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] We eliminate each of these by contradiction, leaving equality as the only possibility.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] We use regular polygons in the same way.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Suppose that the area *C* enclosed by the circle is greater than the area *T* = *cr*/2 of the triangle.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Inscribe a square in the circle, so that its four corners lie on the circle.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Between the square and the circle are four segments.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] If the total area of those gaps, *G*4, is greater than *E*, split each arc in half.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] This makes the inscribed square into an inscribed octagon, and produces eight segments with a smaller total gap, *G*8.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Continue splitting until the total gap area, *Gn*, is less than *E*.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Now the area of the inscribed polygon, *Pn* = *C* − *Gn*, must be greater than that of the triangle.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] But this forces a contradiction, as follows.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Draw a perpendicular from the center to the midpoint of a side of the polygon; its length, *h*, is less than the circle radius.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Also, let each side of the polygon have length *s*; then the sum of the sides is *ns*, which is less than the circle circumference.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The polygon area consists of *n* equal triangles with height *h* and base *s*, thus equals *nhs*/2.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] But since *h* < *r* and *ns* < *c*, the polygon area must be less than the triangle area, *cr*/2, a contradiction.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Therefore, our supposition that *C* might be greater than *T* must be wrong.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Suppose that the area enclosed by the circle is less than the area *T* of the triangle.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Circumscribe a square, so that the midpoint of each edge lies on the circle.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] If the total area gap between the square and the circle, *G*4, is greater than *D*, slice off the corners with circle tangents to make a circumscribed octagon, and continue slicing until the gap area is less than *D*.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The area of the polygon, *Pn*, must be less than *T*.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] For, a perpendicular to the midpoint of each polygon side is a radius, of length *r*.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] And since the total side length is greater than the circumference, the polygon consists of *n* identical triangles with total area greater than *T*.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Again we have a contradiction, so our supposition that *C* might be less than *T* must be wrong as well.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Therefore, it must be the case that the area enclosed by the circle is precisely the same as the area of the triangle.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Following Satō Moshun (Smith & Mikami 1914, pp.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] 130–132), Nicholas of Cusa and Leonardo da Vinci (Beckmann 1976, p.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] 19), we can use inscribed regular polygons in a different way.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Cut the hexagon into six triangles by splitting it from the center.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Two opposite triangles both touch two common diameters; slide them along one so the radial edges are adjacent.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] They now form a parallelogram, with the hexagon sides making two opposite edges, one of which is the base, *s*.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Two radial edges form slanted sides, and the height, *h* is equal to its apothem (as in the Archimedes proof).
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] In fact, we can also assemble all the triangles into one big parallelogram by putting successive pairs next to each other.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The same is true if we increase it to eight sides and so on.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] For a polygon with 2*n* sides, the parallelogram will have a base of length *ns*, and a height *h*.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] As the number of sides increases, the length of the parallelogram base approaches half the circle circumference, and its height approaches the circle radius.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] In the limit, the parallelogram becomes a rectangle with width π*r* and height *r*.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] There are various equivalent definitions of the constant π.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] However, because the circumference of a circle is not a primitive analytical concept, this definition is not suitable in modern rigorous treatments.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] A standard modern definition is that π is equal to twice the least positive root of the cosine function or, equivalently, the half-period of the sine (or cosine) function.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The cosine function can be defined either as a power series, or as the solution of a certain differential equation.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] This avoids any reference to circles in the definition of π, so that statements about the relation of π to the circumference and area of circles are actually theorems, rather than definitions, that follow from the analytical definitions of concepts like "area" and "circumference".
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The integral appearing on the right is an abelian integral whose value is a half-period of the sine function, equal to π.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Thus $C=2\pi R=\pi D$ is seen to be true as a theorem.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] We have indicated where appropriate how each of these proofs can be made totally independent of all trigonometry, but in some cases that requires more sophisticated mathematical ideas than those afforded by elementary calculus.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Using calculus, we can sum the area incrementally, partitioning the disk into thin concentric rings like the layers of an onion.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] This is the method of shell integration in two dimensions.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] For an infinitesimally thin ring of the "onion" of radius *t*, the accumulated area is 2π*t dt*, the circumferential length of the ring times its infinitesimal width (one can approximate this ring by a rectangle with width=2π*t* and height=*dt*).
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] This gives an elementary integral for a disk of radius *r*.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] It is rigorously justified by the multivariate substitution rule in polar coordinates.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Namely, the area is given by a double integral of the constant function 1 over the disk itself.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] which is the same result as obtained above.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] An equivalent rigorous justification, without relying on the special coordinates of trigonometry, uses the coarea formula.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Note ρ is a Lipschitz function whose gradient is a unit vector $|\nabla \rho |=1$ (almost everywhere).
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] We will show that ${\mathcal {L}}^{2}(D)=\pi$ , where ${\mathcal {L}}^{2}$ is the two-dimensional Lebesgue measure in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] We shall assume that the one-dimensional Hausdorff measure of the circle $\rho =r$ is $2\pi r$ , the circumference of the circle of radius *r*.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Similar to the onion proof outlined above, we could exploit calculus in a different way in order to arrive at the formula for the area of a disk.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Consider unwrapping the concentric circles to straight strips.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] This will form a right angled triangle with r as its height and 2πr (being the outer slice of onion) as its base.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The opposite and adjacent angles for this triangle are respectively in degrees 9.0430611..., 80.956939... and in radians 0.1578311...
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Explicitly, we imagine dividing up a circle into triangles, each with a height equal to the circle's radius and a base that is infinitesimally small.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The area of each of these triangles is equal to $1/2\cdot r\cdot du$ .
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The triangle proof can be reformulated as an application of Green's theorem in flux-divergence form (i.e. a two-dimensional version of the divergence theorem), in a way that avoids all mention of trigonometry and the constant π.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Consider the vector field $\mathbf {r} =x\mathbf {i} +y\mathbf {j}$ in the plane.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] where **n** is the unit normal and *ds* is the arc length measure.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The integral of *ds* over the whole circle $\partial D$ is just the arc length, which is its circumference, so this shows that the area *A* enclosed by the circle is equal to $R/2$ times the circumference of the circle.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Note that sin(*d𝜃*) ≈ *d𝜃* due to small angle approximation.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Note that the area of a semicircle of radius *r* can be computed by the integral ${\textstyle \int _{-r}^{r}{\sqrt {r^{2}-x^{2}}}\,dx}$ .
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The last step follows since the trigonometric identity $\cos(\theta )=\sin(\pi /2-\theta )$ implies that $\cos ^{2}\theta$ and $\sin ^{2}\theta$ have equal integrals over the interval $[0,\pi /2]$ , using integration by substitution.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] But on the other hand, since $\cos ^{2}\theta +\sin ^{2}\theta =1$ , the sum of the two integrals is the length of that interval, which is $\pi /2$ .
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Consequently, the integral of $\cos ^{2}\theta$ is equal to half the length of that interval, which is $\pi /4$ .
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Therefore, the area of a circle of radius *r*, which is twice the area of the semi-circle, is equal to $2\cdot {\frac {\pi r^{2}}{2}}=\pi r^{2}$ .
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] This particular proof may appear to beg the question, if the sine and cosine functions involved in the trigonometric substitution are regarded as being defined in relation to circles.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The circle is the closed curve of least perimeter that encloses the maximum area.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Moreover, equality holds in this inequality if and only if the curve is a circle, in which case $A=\pi r^{2}$ and $C=2\pi r$ .
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The calculations Archimedes used to approximate the area numerically were laborious, and he stopped with a polygon of 96 sides.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] A faster method uses ideas of Willebrord Snell (*Cyclometricus*, 1621), further developed by Christiaan Huygens (*De Circuli Magnitudine Inventa*, 1654), described in Gerretsen & Verdenduin (1983, pp.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Given a circle, let *un* be the perimeter of an inscribed regular *n-*gon, and let *Un* be the perimeter of a circumscribed regular *n-*gon.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Then *un* and *Un* are lower and upper bounds for the circumference of the circle that become sharper and sharper as *n* increases, and their average (*un* + *Un*)/2 is an especially good approximation to the circumference.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Starting from a hexagon, Archimedes doubled *n* four times to get a 96-gon, which gave him a good approximation to the circumference of the circle.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] In modern notation, we can reproduce his computation (and go further) as follows.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] For a unit circle, an inscribed hexagon has *u*6 = 6, and a circumscribed hexagon has *U*6 = 4√3.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The last entry of the table has 355⁄113 as one of its best rational approximations; i.e., there is no better approximation among rational numbers with denominator up to 113.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The number 355⁄113 is also an excellent approximation to π, attributed to Chinese mathematician Zu Chongzhi, who named it Milü.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] This approximation is better than any other rational number with denominator less than 16,604.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] This for *n* = 48 gives a better approximation (about 3.14159292) than Archimedes' method for *n* = 768.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Let one side of an inscribed regular *n-*gon have length *sn* and touch the circle at points A and B.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Let A′ be the point opposite A on the circle, so that A′A is a diameter, and A′AB is an inscribed triangle on a diameter.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] By Thales' theorem, this is a right triangle with right angle at B.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Let the length of A′B be *cn*, which we call the complement of *sn*; thus *cn*2+*sn*2 = (2*r*)2.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Let C bisect the arc from A to B, and let C′ be the point opposite C on the circle.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Thus the length of CA is *s*2*n*, the length of C′A is *c*2*n*, and C′CA is itself a right triangle on diameter C′C.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Because C bisects the arc from A to B, C′C perpendicularly bisects the chord from A to B, say at P.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Triangle C′AP is thus a right triangle, and is similar to C′CA since they share the angle at C′.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Thus all three corresponding sides are in the same proportion; in particular, we have C′A : C′C = C′P : C′A and AP : C′A = CA : C′C.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The center of the circle, O, bisects A′A, so we also have triangle OAP similar to A′AB, with OP half the length of A′B.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] In the first equation C′P is C′O+OP, length *r* + ⁠1/2⁠*cn*, and C′C is the diameter, 2*r*.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] If we now circumscribe a regular *n-*gon, with side A″B″ parallel to AB, then OAB and OA″B″ are similar triangles, with A″B″ : AB = OC : OP.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Call the circumscribed side *Sn*; then this is *Sn* : *sn* = 1 : 1⁄2*cn*.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Call the inscribed perimeter *un* = *nsn*, and the circumscribed perimeter *Un* = *nSn*.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] When more efficient methods of finding areas are not available, we can resort to "throwing darts".
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] This Monte Carlo method uses the fact that if random samples are taken uniformly scattered across the surface of a square in which a disk resides, the proportion of samples that hit the disk approximates the ratio of the area of the disk to the area of the square.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] This should be considered a method of last resort for computing the area of a disk (or any shape), as it requires an enormous number of samples to get useful accuracy; an estimate good to 10−*n* requires about 100*n* random samples (Thijssen 2006, p.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] We have seen that by partitioning the disk into an infinite number of pieces we can reassemble the pieces into a rectangle.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] A remarkable fact discovered relatively recently (Laczkovich 1990) is that we can dissect the disk into a large but *finite* number of pieces and then reassemble the pieces into a square of equal area.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] This is called Tarski's circle-squaring problem.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The nature of Laczkovich's proof is such that it proves the existence of such a partition (in fact, of many such partitions) but does not exhibit any particular partition.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Circles can be defined in non-Euclidean geometry, and in particular in the hyperbolic and elliptic planes.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] For example, the unit sphere $S^{2}(1)$ is a model for the two-dimensional elliptic plane.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] It carries an intrinsic metric that arises by measuring geodesic length.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The geodesic circles are the parallels in a geodesic coordinate system.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] More precisely, fix a point $\mathbf {z} \in S^{2}(1)$ that we place at the zenith.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Associated to that zenith is a geodesic polar coordinate system $(\varphi ,\theta )$ , $0\leq \varphi \leq \pi$ , $0\leq \theta <2\pi$ , where **z** is the point $\varphi =0$ .
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] In these coordinates, the geodesic distance from **z** to any other point $\mathbf {x} \in S^{2}(1)$ having coordinates $(\varphi ,\theta )$ is the value of $\varphi$ at **x**.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] A spherical circle is the set of points a geodesic distance *R* from the zenith point **z**.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Equivalently, with a fixed embedding into $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ , the spherical circle of radius $R\leq \pi$ centered at **z** is the set of **x** in $S^{2}(1)$ such that $\mathbf {x} \cdot \mathbf {z} =\cos R$ .
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] We can also measure the area of the spherical disk enclosed within a spherical circle, using the intrinsic surface area measure on the sphere.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Observe that, as an application of L'Hôpital's rule, this tends to the Euclidean area $\pi R^{2}$ in the flat limit $\rho \to \infty$ .
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] These identities are important for comparison inequalities in geometry.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] For example, the area enclosed by a circle of radius *R* in a flat space is always greater than the area of a spherical circle and smaller than a hyperbolic circle, provided all three circles have the same (intrinsic) radius.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Intuitively, this is because the sphere tends to curve back on itself, yielding circles of smaller area than those in the plane, whilst the hyperbolic plane, when immersed into space, develops fringes that produce additional area.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] It is more generally true that the area of the circle of a fixed radius *R* is a strictly decreasing function of the curvature.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] where equality is achieved precisely for the circle.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] We can stretch a disk to form an ellipse.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Because this stretch is a linear transformation of the plane, it has a distortion factor which will change the area but preserve *ratios* of areas.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] This observation can be used to compute the area of an arbitrary ellipse from the area of a unit circle.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Consider the unit circle circumscribed by a square of side length 2.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The transformation sends the circle to an ellipse by stretching or shrinking the horizontal and vertical diameters to the major and minor axes of the ellipse.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The square gets sent to a rectangle circumscribing the ellipse.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] The ratio of the area of the circle to the square is π/4, which means the ratio of the ellipse to the rectangle is also π/4.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Suppose *a* and *b* are the lengths of the major and minor axes of the ellipse.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] Since the area of the rectangle is *ab*, the area of the ellipse is π*ab*/4.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] We can also consider analogous measurements in higher dimensions.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] For example, we may wish to find the volume inside a sphere.
[src:engine-displacement/area-of-a-circle] When we have a formula for the surface area, we can use the same kind of "onion" approach we used for the disk.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] An **automotive battery**, or **car battery**, is a rechargeable battery that is used to start a motor vehicle, and to power lights, screen wiper etc. while the engine is off.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Its main purpose is to provide an electric current to the electric-powered starting motor, which in turn starts the chemically-powered internal combustion engine that actually propels the vehicle.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Once the engine is running, power for the car's electrical systems is still supplied by the battery, with the alternator charging the battery as demands increase or decrease.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Typically, starting uses less than three percent of the battery capacity.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] For this reason, automotive batteries are designed to deliver maximum current for a short period of time.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] They are sometimes referred to as "SLI batteries" for this reason, for starting, lighting and ignition.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] SLI batteries are not designed for deep discharging, and a full discharge can reduce the battery's lifespan.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] As well as starting the engine, an SLI battery supplies the extra power necessary when the vehicle's electrical requirements exceed the supply from the charging system.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] It is also a stabilizer, evening out potentially damaging voltage spikes.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] While the engine is running most of the power is provided by the alternator (or in older vehicles a generator or dynamo), which includes a voltage regulator to keep the output between 13.5 and 14.5 V.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Modern SLI batteries are lead-acid type, using six series-connected cells to provide a nominal 12-volt system (in most passenger vehicles and light trucks), or twelve cells for a 24-volt system in heavy trucks or earth-moving equipment, for example.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Gas explosions can occur at the negative electrode where hydrogen gas can build up due to blocked battery vents or a poorly ventilated setting, combined with an ignition source.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Explosions during engine start-up are typically associated with corroded or dirty battery posts.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] A 1993 study by the US National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said that 31% of vehicle battery explosion injuries occurred while charging the battery.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Close to two-thirds of those injured suffered chemical burns, and nearly three-fourths suffered eye injuries, among other possible injuries.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Electric vehicles (EVs) are powered by a high-voltage electric vehicle battery, but they usually have an automotive battery as well, so that they can use standard automotive accessories which are designed to run on 12 V.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Unlike conventional, internal combustion engined vehicles, EVs don't charge the auxiliary battery with an alternator—instead, they use a DC-to-DC converter to step down the high voltage to the required float-charge voltage (typically around 14 V).
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Further, an electric vehicle does not have a starter motor, thus needs only a limited amount of power and energy from its auxiliary battery.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] As such, Tesla introduced in 2021 a lithium-ion auxiliary battery storing only 99 Wh of energy.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Early cars did not have batteries, as their electrical systems were limited.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Electric power for the ignition was provided by a magneto, the engine was started with a crank, headlights were gas-powered and a bell or bulb-horn was used instead of an electric horn.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Car batteries became widely used around 1920 as cars became equipped with electric starter motors.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] The first starting and charging systems were designed to be 6-volt and positive-ground systems, with the vehicle's chassis directly connected to the positive battery terminal.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Today, almost all road vehicles have a negative ground system.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] The negative battery terminal is connected to the car's chassis.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] The Hudson Motor Car Company was the first to use a standardized battery in 1918 when they started using Battery Council International batteries.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] BCI is the organization that sets the dimensional standards for batteries.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Cars used 6 V electrical systems and batteries until the mid-1950s.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] The changeover from 6 to 12 V happened when bigger engines with higher compression ratios required more electrical power to start.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Smaller cars, which required less power to start stayed with 6 V longer, for example the Volkswagen Beetle in the mid-1960s and the Citroën 2CV in 1970.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] The AGM sealed battery (for automobiles), which did not require refilling, was invented in 1971.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] In the 1990s a 42V electrical system standard was proposed.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] It was intended to allow more powerful electrically driven accessories, and lighter automobile wiring harnesses.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] However, the availability of higher-efficiency motors, new wiring techniques, and digital controls, and a focus on hybrid vehicle systems that use high-voltage starter/generators have largely eliminated the push for switching the main automotive voltages.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] In 2023 Tesla started deliveries of their Cybertruck that uses a 48-volt electrical system, reducing 70% of the wiring in the vehicle.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] An automobile battery is an example of a wet cell battery, with six cells.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Each cell of a lead storage battery consists of alternate plates made of a lead alloy grid filled with sponge lead plates (cathode) or coated with lead dioxide (anode).
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Each cell is filled with a sulfuric acid solution, which is the electrolyte.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Initially, cells each had a filler cap, through which the electrolyte level could be viewed and which allowed water to be added to the cell.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] The filler cap had a small vent hole which allowed hydrogen gas generated during charging to escape from the cell.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] The cells are connected by short heavy straps from the positive plates of one cell to the negative plates of the adjacent cell.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] A pair of heavy terminals, plated with lead to resist corrosion, are mounted at the top, sometimes the side, of the battery.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Early auto batteries used hard rubber cases and wooden plate separators.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Modern units use plastic cases and woven sheets to prevent the plates of a cell from touching and short-circuiting.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] In the past, auto batteries required regular inspection and maintenance to replace water that was decomposed during the operation of the battery.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] "Low-maintenance" (sometimes called "zero-maintenance") batteries use a different alloy for the plate elements, reducing the amount of water decomposed on charging.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] A modern battery may not require additional water over its useful life; some types eliminate the individual filler caps for each cell.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] A weakness of these batteries is that they are very intolerant of deep discharge, such as when the car battery is completely drained by leaving the lights on.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] This coats the lead plate electrodes with lead sulfate deposits and can reduce the battery's lifespan by a third or more.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] VRLA batteries, also known as absorbed glass mat (AGM) batteries are more tolerant of deep discharge but are more expensive.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] VRLA batteries do not permit addition of water to the cell.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] The cells each have an automatic pressure release valve, to protect the case from rupture on severe overcharge or internal failure.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] A VRLA battery cannot spill its electrolyte which makes it particularly useful in vehicles such as motorcycles.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Batteries are typically made of six galvanic cells in a series circuits.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Each cell provides 2.1 volts for a total of 12.6 volts at full charge.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] During discharge, at the negative (lead) terminal a chemical reaction releases electrons to the external circuit, and at the positive (lead oxide) terminal another chemical reaction absorbs electrons from the external circuit.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] This drives the electrons through the external circuit wire (an electrical conductor) to produce an electric current (electricity).
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] As the battery discharges, the acid of the electrolyte reacts with the materials of the plates, changing their surface to lead sulfate.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] When the battery is recharged, the chemical reaction is reversed: the lead sulfate reforms into lead dioxide.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] With the plates restored to their original condition, the process may be repeated.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Some vehicles use other starter batteries.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] For weight savings, the 2010 Porsche 911 GT3 RS has a lithium-ion battery as an option; from 2018 onward, all Kia Niro conventional hybrids feature one as well.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Heavy vehicles may have two batteries in series for a 24 V system or may have series-parallel groups of batteries supplying 24 V.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Batteries are grouped by physical size, type and placement of the terminals, and mounting style.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Battery Council International (BCI) group size specifies a battery's physical dimensions, such as length, width, and height.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] These groups are determined by the organization.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Ampere hours (Ah or A·h) is a unit related to the energy storage capacity of the battery.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] This rating is required by law in Europe.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] The ampere hour rating represents the total current delivered over a period of 20 hours before voltage drops below 10.5 volts while operating at a temperature of 80 °F (26.6 °C).
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] In theory, at 80 °F, a 100 Ah battery should be able to continuously provide 5 amps for 20 hours while maintaining a voltage of at least 10.5 volts.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] The relationship between the Ah capacity and the discharge rate is not linear; as the discharge rate is increased, the capacity decreases.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] A battery with a 100 Ah rating generally will not be able to maintain a voltage above 10.5 volts for 10 hours while being discharged at constant rate of 10 amps.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Capacity also decreases with temperature.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Excess heat is a main cause of battery failures, as when the electrolyte evaporates due to high temperatures, decreasing the effective surface area of the plates exposed to the electrolyte, and leading to sulfation.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Grid corrosion rates increase with temperature.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Also low temperatures can lead to battery failure.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] If the battery is discharged to the point where it can't start the engine, the engine can be jump started via an external source of power.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Once running, the engine can recharge the battery, if the alternator and charging system are undamaged.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Corrosion at the battery terminals can prevent a car from starting due to electrical resistance, which can be prevented by the proper application of dielectric grease.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Sulfation is when the electrodes become coated with a hard layer of lead sulfate, which weakens the battery.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Sulfation can happen when battery is not fully charged and remains discharged.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Sulfated batteries should be charged slowly to prevent damage.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] SLI batteries (starting, lighting, and ignition) are not designed for deep discharge, and their life is reduced when subjected to this.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Starting batteries have plates designed for increased surface area and thus high instant current capability, whereas marine (hybrid) and deep cycle types will have thicker plates and more room at the bottom of the plates for spent plate material to gather before shorting the cell.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Car batteries using lead-antimony plates require regular topping-up with pure water to replace water lost due to electrolysis and evaporation.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] By changing the alloying element to calcium, more recent designs have reduced the rate of water loss.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Modern car batteries have reduced maintenance requirements, and may not provide caps for addition of water to the cells.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Such batteries include extra electrolyte above the plates to allow for losses during the battery life.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Some battery manufacturers include a built-in hydrometer to show the state of charge of the battery.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] The primary wear-out mechanism is the shedding of active material from the battery plates, which accumulates at the bottom of the cells and which may eventually short-circuit the plates.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] This can be substantially reduced by enclosing one set of plates in plastic separator bags, made from a permeable material.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] This allows the electrolyte and ions to pass through but keeps the sludge build up from bridging the plates.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] The sludge largely consists of lead sulfate, which is produced at both electrodes.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Battery recycling of automotive batteries reduces the need for resources required for the manufacture of new batteries, diverts toxic lead from landfills, and prevents the risk of improper disposal.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Once a lead–acid battery ceases to hold a charge, it is deemed a used lead-acid battery (ULAB), which is classified as hazardous waste under the Basel Convention.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] The 12-volt car battery is the most recycled product in the world, according to the United States Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] In the U.S. alone, about 130 million auto batteries a year are replaced, and 99 percent of them are turned in for recycling.[1] However, the recycling may be done incorrectly in unregulated environments.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] As part of global waste trade, ULABs are shipped from industrialized countries to developing countries for disassembly and recuperation of the contents.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] About 97 percent of the lead can be recovered.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Pure Earth estimates that over 12 million people in developing countries are affected by lead contamination from ULAB processing.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] ULAB recycling has been used as an example supporting the pollution haven hypothesis.
[src:engine-displacement/automotive-battery] Following this change, American exports of used lead-acid batteries to Mexico increased four-fold, which was followed by a significant increase in babies born with low birth weight to mothers living within a two-mile (3.2 km) radius of Mexican battery-recycling plants.
[src:engine-displacement/engine-displacement] It is usually expressed using the metric units of cubic centimetres (cc or cm3, equivalent to millilitres) or litres (l or L), or – particularly in the United States – cubic inches (CID, c.i.d., cu in, or in3).
[src:engine-displacement/engine-displacement] The overall displacement for a typical reciprocating piston engine is calculated by multiplying together three values; the distance travelled by the piston (the stroke length), the circular area of the cylinder, and the number of cylinders in the whole engine.
[src:engine-displacement/engine-displacement] Using this formula for non-typical types of engine, such as the Wankel design and the oval-piston type used in Honda NR motorcycles, can sometimes yield misleading results when attempting to compare engines.
[src:engine-displacement/engine-displacement] Manufacturers and regulators may develop and use specialised formulae to determine a comparative nominal displacement for variant engine types.
[src:engine-displacement/engine-displacement] In several countries fees and taxes levied on road vehicles by transport authorities are scaled in proportion to engine displacement.
[src:engine-displacement/engine-displacement] In countries where this is practised, vehicle manufacturers often seek to increase power output through higher-revving engines or turbocharging, instead of increasing the displacement.
[src:engine-displacement/engine-displacement] Wankel engines are able to produce higher power levels for a given displacement.
[src:engine-displacement/engine-displacement] Therefore, they are generally taxed as 1.5 times their stated physical displacement (1.3 litres becomes effectively 2.0, 2.0 becomes effectively 3.0), although actual power outputs can be higher than suggested by this conversion factor.
[src:engine-displacement/engine-displacement] The nominal displacement of a Wankel engine is 3 times smaller than the physical displacement, but this is compensated by the fact that the shaft has 3 times the rotational speed of the rotor.
[src:engine-displacement/engine-displacement] The nominal displacement is the swept volume of a single chamber.
[src:engine-displacement/engine-displacement] Historically, many car model names have included their engine displacement.
[src:engine-displacement/engine-displacement] Examples include the 1923–1930 Cadillac Series 353 (powered by a 353 Cubic inch/5.8-litre engine), and the 1963–1968 BMW 1800 (a 1.8-litre engine) and Lexus LS 400 with a 3,968 cc engine.
[src:engine-displacement/engine-displacement] This was especially common in US muscle cars, like the Ford Mustang Boss 302 and 429, and later GT 5.0L, The Plymouth Roadrunner 383, and the Chevrolet Chevelle SS 396 and 454.
[src:engine-displacement/engine-displacement] However, trends towards downsizing and hybrid/electric drivetrains since 2010 have resulted in far fewer model names being based on the engine displacement.
